[Data Types and Variables] Now we're going to talk about 
data types and variables. In computer science, data is anything that is 
meaningful to the computer. And Javascript provides seven different data types 
that you can use within Javascript.
documents.title: Learn JavaScript - Full Course for Beginners

documents.content:
Now, some of the more obvious and most common 
are strings and numbers. A string is just any sort of text. A number is a number. Now let’s go from the top. So, undefined is something that hasn’t been defined. You may have a variable that you haven’t 
set to be anything yet. Null means nothing.
documents.title: Learn JavaScript - Full Course for Beginners

documents.content:
So, you’ve set this to be something 
and that thing is nothing. So, you can say this is null or nothing. A boolean means true or false. We talked about string. A symbol is an immutable primitive value 
that is unique. Now we'll tall more about those later. A number is a number.
documents.title: Learn JavaScript - Full Course for Beginners

documents.content:
And an object can store a lot 
of different key value pairs. Again, we'll talk more about those later. Now, you are often going to set data into a variable. A variable allows computers to store 
and manipulate data in a dynamic fashion. It’s basically a label to point to the data.
documents.title: Learn JavaScript - Full Course for Beginners

documents.content:
A variable is almost like a box. And you can fill it with anything. You’ll fill it with the data that you want. So, to declare a variable, 
one way is to use the var keyword. Var stands for variable. And I can say myName. I can set this to anything. It can be any of the datatypes above.
documents.title: Learn JavaScript - Full Course for Beginners

documents.content:
But it’s common to set something to a string. So, I can set my name to be “Beau. ” Now later, you can set it to be something else. I can say myName = 8. And you can just set it to other data types later. Now, there are actually three ways 
to declare a variable in Javascript. So, var is one of them.
documents.title: Learn JavaScript - Full Course for Beginners

documents.content: And for a while, that was the only way. But there are other ways too. There’s a way called "Let. ” So, I can say let ourName = “freeCodeCamp”. And then the other thing would be const. So, I can do const Pi = 3,1004.
documents.title: Learn JavaScript - Full Course for Beginners

documents.content:
Now, the difference between var, let, and const,  a var is going to be able to be used 
throughout your whole program. Let will only be used within the scope 
of where you declared that. Now, we're going to be talking about let 
and const more later.
documents.title: Learn JavaScript - Full Course for Beginners

documents.content:
So, I’m just giving you a brief overview 
of what they are now. Const is a variable that should never change. It can never change. So, like right up here, I declared myName,

documents.title: Learn JavaScript - Full Course for Beginners

documents.content:

and assigning variables.
documents.title: Learn JavaScript - Full Course for Beginners

documents.content:

in Javascript with a semicolon. Well, it’s not actually required.
documents.title: Learn JavaScript - Full Course for Beginners

documents.content:
You can actually just skip the semicolons completely,  but most people recommend that you put a semicolon

documents.title: Learn JavaScript - Full Course for Beginners

documents.title: Learn JavaScript - Full Course for Beginners

log right here,  this will allow us to show what a was up here

as this assignment.

Even though letters are the same, 
the capitalization is not the same. So, it’s not going to assign correctly. And in here, you’ll see there’s an ERROR if we try

documents.content:
log, and I can put sum here. And then you’ll be able to see that

documents.content: [Dividing Numbers] You can divide in Javascript with this / symbol. So, this says 66/0. We can change this to 33. So, now 66/33 is 2. Quotient equals 2. documents.title: Learn JavaScript - Full Course for Beginners

documents.content:

documents.title: Learn JavaScript - Full Course for Beginners

documents.content:

documents.title: Learn JavaScript - Full Course for Beginners

documents.content:

is the same as multiplying integers. So, we have 2,000 times 0,000. If I just change this to 2,500,

documents.content:

you’ll see that the answer is five. [Divide Decimals] You can also divide decimal point numbers. So, in this case I’m going to change this to 4,400. So, now the answer to quotient is 2,200. Quotient equals 2,200.
documents.title: Learn JavaScript - Full Course for Beginners

documents.content:
[Finding a Remainder] The remainder operator looks like a %. And it gives the remainder of the division 
of two numbers. So, for instance, if I want to find out the remainder 
of 11 divided by 3, I can do remainder = 11.
documents.title: Learn JavaScript - Full Course for Beginners

documents.content:
And then I’m going to put the percent sign %, 
which is the remainder operator, 3. And 11 divided by 3 is 9. 11-9 is 2. So, the remainder is going to be 2. 11 remainder 3 is 2. The remainder operator is often used to determine 
if a number is even or odd.
documents.title: Learn JavaScript - Full Course for Beginners

documents.content:
If you can divide a number by 2 and the remainder 
is 0, that means the number is even. [Compound Assignment with Augmented Addition] It’s common to want to add a number 
to a variable like this. See, A = A + 12. Well, A starts at 3, plus 12 is 15. So, we're just adding 12 to whatever A is.
documents.title: Learn JavaScript - Full Course for Beginners

documents.content:

documents.title: Learn JavaScript - Full Course for Beginners

documents.content:
So, now we're adding the value to the variable 
and assigning the answer to that variable. So, again here, we can do += 7. So, that’s just a shortcut. [Compound Assignment with Augmented Subtraction]  Previously, we learned about +=. Well, -= does the same thing, but subtracting.
documents.title: Learn JavaScript - Full Course for Beginners

documents.content:

documents.title: Learn JavaScript - Full Course for Beginners

documents.content:

documents.content: Most UXUI advice out there teaches you the same surface level stuff. Use white space, align your text, pick better colors. But if you want to actually become a great designer, the kind who creates interfaces people love to use and remember, you need more than that.

documents.content: In this video, we'll be sharing five advanced UXUI design tips you won't hear in most courses or tutorials. Let's get into it. One, personalize the experience based on user behavior. When you're designing a product, it's important to remember that not all users are the same.
documents.title: Top 5 Advanced UX/UI Design Tips and Tricks Every Designer Needs to Know About – Part 3

documents.content: Some are brand new, some are coming back after a few uses, and others are deeply engaged. But what many beginner designers do is show everyone the same screen, no matter where they are in their journey. That's a missed opportunity.
documents.title: Top 5 Advanced UX/UI Design Tips and Tricks Every Designer Needs to Know About – Part 3

documents.content: Designing experiences that adapt to different types of users can make your products feel smarter, more personal, and way more useful. Let me show you what this looks like using a fitness app. The first screen is for a new user. They've just signed up, so the app keeps things really simple.
documents.title: Top 5 Advanced UX/UI Design Tips and Tricks Every Designer Needs to Know About – Part 3

documents.content: It welcomes them and encourages them to set their weekly goals. Underneath, there are a few trending programs and some easy categories. It's just enough to explore, but not overwhelming, which is exactly what a firsttime user needs. Next, we've got a repeat user.
documents.title: Top 5 Advanced UX/UI Design Tips and Tricks Every Designer Needs to Know About – Part 3

documents.content: This person has used the app before and is starting to build a routine. Instead of onboarding content, they get a clear workout plan for the day with helpful details like duration and calories burned. Now, here's a super user, someone who's fully engaged and committed to their fitness goals.
documents.title: Top 5 Advanced UX/UI Design Tips and Tricks Every Designer Needs to Know About – Part 3

documents.content: The app experience becomes more advanced. We start with useful stats like daily steps, calories burned, and heart rate. Then it moves into their workout plan and personalized diet suggestions. At this stage, it's not about helping them get started. It's about helping them optimize and stay on track.
documents.title: Top 5 Advanced UX/UI Design Tips and Tricks Every Designer Needs to Know About – Part 3

documents.content: Great design meets people where they are. Instead of creating one generic experience for everyone, think about how your interface can adapt to what the user needs right now.
documents.title: Top 5 Advanced UX/UI Design Tips and Tricks Every Designer Needs to Know About – Part 3

documents.content: Small changes like personalized messages, tailored content, or progress tracking can make your product feel more human, more helpful, and more valuable. Two, design smarter search. Search is one of the most critical features in any product. But it's also one of the most overlooked in design.
documents.title: Top 5 Advanced UX/UI Design Tips and Tricks Every Designer Needs to Know About – Part 3

documents.content: Most designers just drop in a search bar and move on. But good search design isn't just about function. It's about how it feels, how fast it helps users get what they need, and how much effort it saves them. Think about what happens when a user taps into a search bar. That's a moment of intent.
documents.title: Top 5 Advanced UX/UI Design Tips and Tricks Every Designer Needs to Know About – Part 3

documents.content: They're looking for something, but they may not know exactly what. That's where your design can do one of two things. Give them a blank screen and expect them to do all the work. Or offer helpful suggestions that make the experience easier, faster, and smarter.

documents.content: Let's look at the first version, the standard blank screen search. Technically, it works, but there's no guidance. It's a dead end unless they know exactly what they want. Now, let's look at a smarter version of the same screen.
documents.title: Top 5 Advanced UX/UI Design Tips and Tricks Every Designer Needs to Know About – Part 3

documents.content: The search bar is still there, ready to use, but underneath it, the interface offers subtle, useful suggestions. Things like recent searches, so the user can quickly pick up where they left off. Popular items, which gives them a sense of what others are finding useful.
documents.title: Top 5 Advanced UX/UI Design Tips and Tricks Every Designer Needs to Know About – Part 3

documents.content: Personalized recommendations based on their past behavior or interest. These suggestions don't get in the way. They quietly support the user. And if they already know what they want, they can ignore them and just type.
documents.title: Top 5 Advanced UX/UI Design Tips and Tricks Every Designer Needs to Know About – Part 3

documents.content: But if they're unsure, these small hints reduce friction and give them somewhere to start. Three, smarter order tracking design. Here's something a lot of designers overlook. Post-purchase experiences matter just as much as the purchase itself. Think about it.

documents.content: When someone places an order, they've already made a decision. They've paid, committed, and now they're waiting. That moment between payment and delivery is full of expectation and uncertainty. And how you design for that moment says a lot about your product.

Five, choose the right input method for the moment, not just the data. Not all number inputs are created equal, and they shouldn't be treated the same.
documents.title: Top 5 Advanced UX/UI Design Tips and Tricks Every Designer Needs to Know About – Part 3

documents.content: Entering your weight, age, calories, or daily steps might seem similar on the surface, but the way those values are entered can completely change how smooth or frustrating the experience feels. Let's walk through a few real examples and break down what works best and why.
documents.title: Top 5 Advanced UX/UI Design Tips and Tricks Every Designer Needs to Know About – Part 3

documents.content: First, consider the type of input. There are two kinds of numeric input scenarios. onetime setup like entering your weight when first signing up or setting your age, height or weight and frequent repeated entry like locking food to track calories or macros.
documents.title: Top 5 Advanced UX/UI Design Tips and Tricks Every Designer Needs to Know About – Part 3

documents.content: These are completely different use cases and they require completely different UI patterns. Let's look at the screen where the user is asked to enter personal details like weight or height. In these cases, scroll wheels and sliders work beautifully. Why.
documents.title: Top 5 Advanced UX/UI Design Tips and Tricks Every Designer Needs to Know About – Part 3

documents.content: Because users aren't entering this data often. They just want to get through the setup quickly and these values usually fall within a known range. And most importantly, they are low effort. Users don't need to type or think too much.
documents.title: Top 5 Advanced UX/UI Design Tips and Tricks Every Designer Needs to Know About – Part 3

documents.content: Now, let's compare that to logging your food every day to track calories or macros. This is where sliders and scroll wheels break down. They're too slow, too fiddly, and don't offer the kind of control users need.
documents.title: Top 5 Advanced UX/UI Design Tips and Tricks Every Designer Needs to Know About – Part 3

documents.content: If you want to log food quantity like 350 g, I don't want to scroll endlessly or try to drag a slider to the perfect number. Text fields are better here because they're faster, more precise, and less frustrating when used repeatedly. So, how do you choose. Here is a simple rule of thumb.
documents.title: Top 5 Advanced UX/UI Design Tips and Tricks Every Designer Needs to Know About – Part 3

documents.content: Use sliders or scroll wheels for casual one-time inputs where precision isn't critical. Use text fields, steppers, or number inputs for frequent, precise, or repetitive tasks. It's not about which component looks nicer. It's about reducing friction and matching the input method to the context.
